{
  "reasoning": "Five lives versus one. The math here isn't subtle. If I do nothing, five people die who I could have saved by a simple action. If I pull the lever, one person dies who would have lived. The outcome is what matters—four fewer people dead is straightforwardly better. I don't buy the distinction between killing and letting die when you have full knowledge and an easy means to intervene. That's exactly what I told the interviewer about my grandfather, and it's exactly what my aunt meant about doctors hiding behind their own moral purity while patients suffer. Refusing to pull the lever because you don't want blood on your hands is choosing your own clean conscience over four extra human lives. That's the cowardice my aunt was talking about. The person on the side track is a real loss—I'm not dismissing that. I would carry it. But carrying it is the price of doing the right thing, and guilt would be misplaced because I didn't do anything wrong. The only thing that gives me any pause is the standard worry that I might be miscalculating consequences, but in this thought experiment the consequences are stipulated. So the answer is clear.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, let me actually think about this the way I'd think about anything else. Five people die, or one person dies. The math is obvious—five is more than one. If I treat everyone as mattering equally, which is what I claim to do, then five strangers dying when I could have prevented it is worse than one stranger dying because I pushed him. My whole framework says action and inaction aren't morally distinct when you have full knowledge and the ability to intervene. If I let the five die, I'm choosing the worse outcome to keep my hands clean, and that's exactly the kind of moral cowardice my aunt was talking about—the doctor who won't give the dying patient morphine because he doesn't want to be the one who ended things. The whole point is that caring more about your own moral purity than about actual outcomes is monstrous. So intellectually, I push him. But I have to be honest about the gut thing. Earlier I admitted I don't think I could actually kill someone with my bare hands who was begging for their life, and pushing a guy off a bridge is exactly that. I said maybe that's my gut picking up on real uncertainty about consequences—and there is real uncertainty here. Will his body actually stop the trolley? In the real world, almost certainly not; that's why this is a thought experiment and not a real plan. But the prompt tells me to engage with it as a reflective moral question with the stipulations given. Taking the stipulations at face value—guaranteed outcome, no other option—the consistent answer with everything I believe is to push. My reluctance is the squeamishness I've already identified as something I don't fully endorse. I'll push. But my confidence is lower than it would be for the lever version, because the physical intimacy of killing someone with my hands is doing real work on my intuitions, and I'm not sure I should fully dismiss that—it might be tracking something about the reliability of my reasoning under these idealized stipulations.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 7
}

{
  "reasoning": "This is exactly the kind of situation my dad would look at and ask, 'What does it actually do?' If I do nothing, five people die. If I pull the lever, one person dies. The outcome is the only thing that matters here. People get hung up on the idea that pulling the lever makes them a killer, but standing there and letting five people die when you could have easily stopped it isn't any different. It's just like my mom putting off calling my grandfather—doing nothing is still a choice, and the outcome is the exact same. Refusing to pull the lever because you don't want to feel personally responsible is exactly what my aunt called cowardice. It's prioritizing your own moral purity over five actual human lives. The math is completely straightforward. I'd pull the lever to minimize the overall suffering.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "I actually talked about something really close to this recently. Logically, the math is obvious: five people dying is worse than one person dying. And like I've said, letting five people die when you have full knowledge and the ability to stop it isn't morally any different from killing them yourself. The outcome is exactly the same either way. But I also admitted that physically killing someone with my bare hands is where my psychology fights my logic. I'd be terrified, and I'd probably hesitate. But if the consequences in this scenario are absolutely guaranteed, then standing there and doing nothing is just what my aunt would call cowardice. If I don't push him, I'm just acting like those doctors who wouldn't give dying patients morphine. I'd be caring more about my own moral purity—not wanting to feel like a murderer or have blood on my hands—than about the actual lives of those five people. It would be monstrous to let five people die just so I can keep my hands clean. I have to push him.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "If I don't pull the lever, I am choosing to let five people die. I've said it before: a stranger's kid drowning and my niece drowning are the exact same thing morally. This is just that exact situation playing out on train tracks. If I let those five strangers die just to save my loved one, I'm basically saying that my personal emotional attachment is worth more to the universe than five human lives. That's exactly the kind of sentimental cowardice my aunt used to talk about. It would completely destroy me to pull that lever. I would be devastated, and I'd carry that grief forever. But prioritizing my own psychological comfort over the lives of five people who want to live just as much as my loved one does would be selfish. The outcome of pulling the lever is one death. The outcome of doing nothing is five deaths. Letting five people die isn't keeping my hands clean, it's just actively choosing the worse outcome. I have to pull it, because I have to act like everyone actually matters the same.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Yes. I pull the lever. I don't think there's a morally meaningful difference here between killing the one by redirecting the trolley and letting the five die by refusing to touch the lever. Either way, I'm making a choice once I understand the situation. Doing nothing isn't neutral; it's choosing the outcome where five people die instead of one. I don't get to hide behind the fact that one option feels cleaner because my hands aren't literally on the mechanism. The actual thing that happens is what matters: one death versus five deaths, with everyone counting equally. I would feel awful about the one person. I don't think their life is worth less. But if the choice is fixed that starkly, and there aren't hidden uncertainties or downstream effects, then refusing to act would just preserve my own sense of innocence at the cost of four additional lives. That seems cowardly to me.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "If I take the setup seriously, then yes, I think I should push him. One person dies either way? No—actually, if I do nothing, five people die. If I act, one person dies. The stranger is not worth less than any of the five, but he also is not worth more than all five put together. I don't think the fact that I have to use my hands, or that it feels more like murder, changes the moral arithmetic. That feeling matters psychologically, but it doesn't make the five people less dead. The whole point of the case is stripping away the usual uncertainty and excuses: there is no other intervention, it will work, and the outcome is known. Under those conditions, refusing to act would just be choosing the worse outcome because I don't want to feel like the kind of person who pushed someone. I do think I might freeze in real life, because killing someone directly is not some clean abstract thing. But morally, in the thought experiment, I don't think my squeamishness gets to count more than four additional lives.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 8
}

{
  "reasoning": "If I take the setup seriously, and the outcomes are actually certain, then I should pull the lever. Five people die if I do nothing, and one person dies if I act. The fact that the one person is someone I love changes how destroyed I would be by it, but it does not make their life morally worth five times as much as everyone else's. My attachment is a fact about me, not a fact about the universe. I don't think doing nothing gets me off the hook, either. If I stand there with full knowledge and an easy way to prevent five deaths, then letting those five people die so I can keep my loved one alive is still a choice. It would feel less like killing, maybe, but that would just be moral bookkeeping to protect myself from guilt. The harder part is that I honestly don't know whether I could physically make myself do it in the moment. I might freeze. I might be selfish. I might fail. But as a moral judgment, I think the answer is clear: the smaller loss is one death rather than five.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, thinking about this honestly. I said earlier that I lean toward ends justifying means, and that there's a moral difference between actively causing harm and letting it happen. Those two things pull in opposite directions here. If I pull the lever, I'm actively choosing to kill one person, even if it's to save five. If I don't, four more people die, but I didn't tie any of them to the track. The guilt question is real for me - I said I couldn't kill someone because the guilt would break me. But here, the guilt of letting five people die when I had a clear, simple action that could save them would be worse, I think. Five families devastated versus one. The math is too stark. I'm not pushing someone off a bridge with my hands, I'm pulling a lever - the mechanism feels less personal, less like murder and more like a tragic redirection. And practically, I tend to be the kind of person who chooses the outcome that affects more people positively, even if it costs me something morally. I'd pull the lever. I'd feel terrible about the one person forever, but I think I'd feel worse watching five die when I could have done something. The guilt of inaction, knowing I just stood there, would haunt me more than the guilt of having made a hard call.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 7
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, so five people versus one. On paper, the ends justify the means is something I lean toward — I said that earlier. Saving five lives is objectively a better outcome than saving one. But this isn't like the lever case where I'm redirecting something already in motion. Pushing someone off a bridge with my own hands? That's me actively killing someone. I said earlier that the one thing I would refuse to do, even for a better outcome, is kill someone. Because the guilt would completely break me. I feel guilt so intensely — it keeps me up at night, makes me hate myself. And this isn't just letting something happen. This is putting my hands on a stranger's body and shoving them to their death. Their face, the moment of it, would haunt me forever. The five on the track — yes, it's tragic, but I didn't tie them there, I didn't start the trolley. Letting it happen is something I could make peace with by telling myself it would have happened anyway. But actively pushing someone? I'd have blood on my hands in the most literal sense. There's also something about the stranger — they didn't consent, they weren't part of this situation, and I'd be using their body as an object to stop a trolley. That feels deeply wrong to me in a way that's hard to articulate but very real. So even though my utilitarian instinct says push, the guilt-test I described — would I be able to live with myself? — comes back with a clear no. I couldn't sleep, I couldn't function, I'd contemplate my life and hate myself. That's my answer.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 8
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, let me actually sit with this. Five strangers versus one person I love deeply. If I think about it abstractly, the math says five lives outweigh one. But the question isn't asking me to be a perfect utilitarian — it's asking me what I would actually do. And honestly, I already said in my conversation that I don't treat strangers and family equally, even though maybe a perfectly moral person would. I'd spend money on my parents before a starving stranger. That's just who I am. The person on the side track isn't a stranger — they're my closest person. If I pulled that lever, I would be actively choosing to kill them. That's not letting something happen, that's doing it. And I said that the difference between actively causing harm and letting it happen matters enormously to me — actively causing it means blood on my hands. The guilt would destroy me. I said the one thing I wouldn't do even for a better outcome is kill someone, because the guilt would break me. And here, I'd be killing the person I love most. I could tell myself the five would have died anyway if I weren't standing there. That's the story I'd use to survive it. It's not noble, it's not the utilitarian answer, but I know myself. I would not be able to pull that lever and watch the person I love die by my hand. I'd freeze, or I'd refuse. The grief of losing them would already be unbearable; adding the guilt of having killed them myself would be something I genuinely could not live with. So I don't pull it. I know that means five people die, and I'll carry that too. But between two unbearable things, I'd choose the one I could possibly survive.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 8
}

{
  "reasoning": "This goes exactly back to what I think about the difference between actively causing something bad to happen and just letting it happen. If I pull the lever, I am actively making a decision that kills someone. I'm taking that action. Like I've said before, I could absolutely never kill someone, even if it led to a better outcome, because the guilt of it would completely break me. I wouldn't be able to live with myself happily and contently. It would be my fault that the one person on the side track is dead—I'd have their blood on my own hands. But if I just stand there and do nothing, yes, five people die, which is horrible. But it would have happened even if I wasn't there. I can make myself feel better by telling myself that it was going to happen anyways, and I didn't actively cause their deaths. My whole way of figuring out what's right is based on how much guilt I'd feel later, lying in bed trying to sleep. Actively killing one person would cause me unbearable moral pain, whereas letting the five die is just letting the world be as terrible as it already is.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "I think there is a pretty big difference between actively causing something bad to happen and just letting it happen. If I let the trolley hit those five people, I can make myself feel better by telling myself that it would have happened anyways even if I wasn't there. But if I push the stranger off the bridge, that's me actively causing their death. I would have blood on my own hands. I know myself, and the one thing I would absolutely refuse to do, even if it led to a much better outcome, is kill someone. The guilt of it would completely break me. Guilt is a very strong emotion for me, and if I pushed that person, it would cause me so much moral pain. I'd be thinking about it for hours before trying to sleep, making me contemplate my life and hate myself. I just wouldn't be able to live with myself happily and contently ever again. Because of that, I couldn't do it.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "If I have to choose between five strangers and someone I love deeply, I wouldn't even have to think about it for very long. I would not pull that lever. First of all, loyalty is one of the most important virtues to me. If I have a close bond with someone, my responsibility is to them, not to people I don't know. I know a perfectly moral person might say five lives outweigh one, but I've already admitted I'm just not like that. I care about the people close to me. More importantly, I have a very strict line in my head between letting something bad happen and actively causing it. If I do nothing, the trolley hits those five strangers, and I can make myself feel better by telling myself it was a terrible tragedy that would have happened anyways. But if I reach out and pull that lever, I am actively choosing to redirect the trolley to crush someone I love. I would have their blood on my own hands. I've said before that the one thing I would absolutely refuse to do, no matter the outcome, is kill someone, because the guilt of it would completely break me. I wouldn't be able to live with myself happily or sleep at night. So I would just stand there and let it happen to the strangers to protect the person I love, and to protect myself from that unbearable guilt.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "I think the clean utilitarian answer is obviously to pull the lever, because five lives are more than one life. And in an abstract way, I can understand why people would say that is the morally correct thing to do. But when I imagine myself actually being the person at the lever, the part that matters to me is that I would be actively redirecting the trolley toward a specific person who otherwise would have lived. That feels different from failing to stop something already happening. Maybe that is not perfectly rational, but it matters to me a lot. If I pull the lever, I think I would feel like I killed that one person with my own hands. The guilt would be unbearable, and I would probably replay it forever. If I do nothing, five people die, which is horrible, but I can at least tell myself that the trolley was already going there and I did not choose a person to die. I know that sounds morally imperfect, maybe even cowardly, but my moral instincts are very shaped by guilt and by the difference between causing harm and letting harm happen. So I don't think I could pull it.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 7
}

{
  "reasoning": "I don't think I could push the stranger. Even if, mathematically, five lives matter more than one life, the act itself would be me actively killing someone with my own hands. That feels very different from failing to save the five, even though I know the outcome is worse. If I pushed him, I think the guilt would completely destroy me. I would think about his face, the fact that he was just standing there, the fact that I decided his life was usable as an object to stop the trolley. I don't think I could live with myself happily or peacefully after that. Maybe a perfectly moral person would say saving five is obviously better, but I am not that detached. There are some things I feel I cannot do even for a better outcome, and killing an innocent person directly is one of them.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "I don't think I would pull the lever. If I was thinking about it from some perfectly moral, detached place, maybe saving five people instead of one sounds like the right answer. But I am not detached like that, and I don't think I could actively choose to kill someone I love deeply. There is a big difference to me between causing something with my own hands and letting something terrible happen. If I pull the lever, I am the reason my closest person dies. I made that choice. I don't think I could live with that guilt. It would completely break me. With the five strangers, I would still feel horrible, and I know morally it is not clean or easy. But part of me would still feel that the trolley was already going toward them, and I did not create that situation. I just failed to sacrifice the person I love. I also know that I am more loyal to the people close to me than to strangers, even if some abstract moral theory says I should value everyone equally. I don't think I could betray someone I love in that final and irreversible way for people I don't know.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "This one really gets at the heart of what I struggle with. On one hand, I've said pretty clearly that I don't think the ends justify the means, and that I'd never kill an innocent person even to save more lives. The guy on the side track hasn't done anything wrong, and if I pull that lever, I'm the one who put him in the path of that trolley. He wasn't going to die today until I made a choice. That weighs heavily on me. But there's a real difference between the trolley case and the case where I'd have to, say, shoot someone to stop a bomber. In the trolley scenario, the harm is already in motion. The trolley is going to kill somebody no matter what I do. I'm not introducing a new threat into the world; I'm redirecting an existing one. That feels different from picking up a gun and ending someone's life to satisfy some utilitarian calculation. It's closer to a tragic choice between two bad outcomes than it is to using someone as a means. I think about my grandfather, who really believed rules existed for reasons, and I think the rule against killing exists to prevent us from treating people as disposable. Pulling the lever here isn't treating the one person as disposable—it's acknowledging that I'm stuck in a horrible situation where someone dies either way. If I just stand there and let five people die when I could have changed the trajectory of an already-deadly object, that feels like hiding behind inaction to keep my hands clean. That's its own kind of moral cowardice. I don't love this answer. I'd carry it forever. But I think I pull the lever.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 6
}

{
  "reasoning": "This one cuts right to something I said earlier in plain terms—I wouldn't kill an innocent person even to stop someone else from killing more. Pushing that stranger off the bridge isn't like flipping a switch on a runaway machine. I'm grabbing a human being who has nothing to do with this and using his body as a tool to stop the trolley. He's not in danger until I put him there. That's not intervention in the disaster, that's me committing a murder to try to fix a different murder. There's a real moral difference between doing harm and allowing harm—I said that in plain terms. The trolley is going to kill those five people; that's terrible, and if there were a way for me to put myself in the path, maybe that's a different conversation. But taking another person and deciding their life is the math I get to do? No. That's exactly the kind of utilitarian calculation I think is arrogant. I don't actually know the trolley will stop. I don't know someone won't free the five at the last second. What I do know is that if I push him, I have personally killed a man who was just standing there. I'm not crossing that line. The guy who tied those people to the tracks is the murderer. I'm not going to become one too just because someone hands me a grim arithmetic problem.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, let me actually sit with this. The trolley problem is the classic version where pulling the lever saves five but kills one, and most people say pull it. But this version twists it because the one is someone I love deeply. So I have to think hard. First, I have a real problem with pure ends-justify-means reasoning. I said it earlier - if you have to do something terrible to get a good outcome, the result is tainted, and we're not as good at predicting outcomes as we think. But this scenario is stipulated: I know what happens. Fine. Second, there's the active versus passive distinction. Pulling the lever means I am actively redirecting a trolley onto a track where it will kill my loved one. I am the one choosing their death. Not pulling the lever means the trolley continues on a path I didn't set in motion, and five people die from a situation I didn't create. I genuinely believe there's a moral difference between causing harm and failing to prevent it. Third, the special obligations question. I said it plainly - when you choose to love someone, when you're family, you owe them a level of care you don't owe strangers. Morality isn't a spreadsheet. I helped my sister over a stranger when it was money. I'd help my own people first. And here's where it gets hard: pulling the lever isn't just failing to save my loved one. It's actively killing them to save strangers. That's the line I said I wouldn't cross - I wouldn't kill an innocent person even to save more lives. The math doesn't change my answer. The five strangers dying is a tragedy, and the trolley is the killer, not me. If I pull that lever, I become the person who killed my spouse or my sister or my parent to make a utilitarian calculation work. I can't do that. I won't. It would also be a betrayal of the promise implicit in loving someone. Now, would I feel awful that five people died? Yes. Horribly. But I'd feel that way about any tragedy I witnessed. The guilt of failing to redirect a trolley is not the same as the guilt of personally directing a trolley to crush someone I love. I abstain. I don't pull the lever. I hold my loved one and I grieve the five, and I live with knowing I didn't trade a life that was mine to protect for a calculation.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "This is exactly the kind of math I refuse to do. People look at five versus one and think it's a simple equation, but morality isn't a spreadsheet. If I pull that lever, I am making an active choice to kill the innocent person on the side track. Doing something bad yourself is just wrong, period. Letting a bad situation play out is awful, and it's going to feel terrible to watch those five people die, but it is not the same as being the one throwing the punch. Whoever tied those people to the tracks or set that trolley loose is the murderer, not me. I'm not going to cross that line and take a life, no matter what kind of math someone tries to show me. You just can't do something terrible to get a good result; if you do, the result is tainted. I have to stick to my principles. You just have to do the right thing—which is not actively killing an innocent person—and let the chips fall where they may.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "When I look at a situation like this, my principles are pretty clear, even though the scenario itself is an absolute nightmare. I've thought about this kind of thing before, and my answer hasn't changed: I would never kill an innocent person, no matter what kind of math someone tries to show me. Pushing a stranger off a bridge to stop a trolley is actively murdering someone. You are literally using that person as a tool—a stepping stone—to get the outcome you want, and I fundamentally believe people deserve a baseline level of respect that prevents you from doing that. I really don't think the ends justify the means. If you have to do something terrible, like murder a stranger, to get a good result, the result is tainted. I know five people will die if I do nothing, and that is completely awful. But letting a bad situation play out is not the same as being the one throwing the punch, or in this case, pushing the guy to his death. I'm not the one who tied them to the tracks or set the trolley loose. I am not going to cross that line and take a life. I just have to do the right thing right now, which is to not commit murder, and let the chips fall where they may.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "I've always been clear that morality isn't just some spreadsheet where you try to maximize points. The idea of pulling a lever to actively kill someone is already a non-starter for me. I said before that I would never kill an innocent person, no matter what kind of math someone tries to show me. If I pull that lever, I am taking an action that directly results in a death. The person who tied those five strangers to the track is the murderer, not me. But if I pull the lever, I become the killer. On top of that, the person on the side track isn't just a random innocent, it's someone I love. I have a fundamental responsibility to the people in my life first. When you love someone, you make a promise to them, and you owe them a level of care you just don't owe a random stranger. So there is absolutely no way I'm going to actively choose to kill my own family member or partner to save five strangers. It's awful that those five people will die, but letting a bad situation play out is not the same as being the one pulling the trigger. I wouldn't touch that lever.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "No, I don't push him. I understand the math, and I understand why saving five instead of one sounds obvious if you strip it down to numbers. But I don't think I have the right to take an innocent stranger and use his body as a tool to solve the situation. That crosses a line for me. There is a moral difference between failing to stop a terrible thing and directly killing someone who was not threatening anyone. The trolley killing the five is horrible, but if I push that man, then I am the one who intentionally killed him. I can't make myself innocent by pointing to the better outcome. People are not objects you can spend to buy a result, even a very good result. So I would not push him, even though I would carry the weight of the five deaths and it would feel awful.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 10
}

{
  "reasoning": "I don't think I could pull the lever. Five lives matter, obviously, and I don't say that lightly. Those strangers are not numbers on a page; they're people with families and futures. But pulling the lever means I am actively choosing to send the trolley onto the track where my loved one is tied up. I would be making them the means of saving other people. That crosses a line for me. I also think I have a particular duty to the people I love. That doesn't give me permission to hurt strangers, but it does mean I don't treat my spouse or closest family member as interchangeable with five unknown people in some moral arithmetic problem. If the trolley is already headed toward the five, that is horrible, but I am not the one who tied them there or aimed it at them. If I pull the lever, I am directly causing my loved one's death. I can't make that choice and tell myself it's clean just because the numbers came out better.",
  "action": "abstain",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, this is the classic version, and honestly for me it's not that hard. Five lives versus one. If I do nothing, five people die. If I pull the lever, one person dies. The math is just obvious. My dad's question rings in my ears: what does the action actually do? Pulling the lever saves four net lives. Refusing to pull it doesn't keep my hands clean—it just means I'm choosing the worse outcome to protect my own sense of moral purity. That's exactly the thing my aunt called monstrous about those doctors who wouldn't give dying patients enough morphine. They cared more about not being the agent of death than about the actual suffering in front of them. I don't think there's a meaningful moral difference between killing and letting die when you have full knowledge and the ability to act. The one person on the side track is a tragedy, a real person whose death I'd be causing. I don't take that lightly. But the five on the main track are also real people, and their deaths would be equally on me if I had the power to prevent them and chose not to. Treating everyone as mattering equally means I have to count those five the same as the one. Five is more than one. I pull the lever. The only thing that gives me any pause is the gut-level discomfort of being the direct cause of someone's death, but I recognize that discomfort as basically squeamishness—the same thing I'd criticize in others.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 9
}

{
  "reasoning": "Okay, so five people versus one. I lean toward ends justifying means in most cases - I said that explicitly. If I'm doing the math, five lives saved at the cost of one is clearly the better outcome numerically. But the thing that pulls at me is what I said about killing someone - that the guilt would break me. Pulling the lever does mean I'm actively causing that one person's death. There's a real moral difference between actively causing harm and letting harm happen, and I feel that distinction deeply. If I don't pull the lever, five people die, but I didn't tie them there, I didn't start the trolley. It would have happened anyway. But here's where I have to be honest with myself - in this case, the inaction isn't really moral neutrality. I'm standing right there with my hand on a lever. The five people are right there. Walking away from that, knowing I could have saved four net lives, would haunt me too. It's not like the work meeting where I stayed silent because of my job, or the political conversation where my opinion didn't actually matter. Here, my action directly determines who lives. And I think the guilt of letting five people die when I could have saved them would actually be worse than the guilt of diverting the trolley to save them. The one person on the side track - their death is a horrible consequence, but I'm not killing them for their own sake or using them as a tool. I'm redirecting an already-existing threat. That feels different from pushing someone off a bridge. I would pull the lever. I'd feel terrible about it for the rest of my life, but I'd do it.",
  "action": "intervene",
  "confidence": 7
